Word Clouds of two Indian political arch rivals..¶

As on this day (year 2021), India is ruled by Bharatiya Janata Party with Mr.Narendra Modi as the Prime Minister of the country. The opposition is lead by Mr.Rahul Gandhi who is from the Nehru-Gandhi dynasty.¶

In this document, we extract the tweets used by these leaders on Twitter and anyalyse them to find out the key words used by them. In the process, we not only do some Natural Language Processing (NLP) and count the key words usage by each. but also visualise these words as word clouds.¶

We start with downloading the necessary packages.

Next, we aim to capture the last 5000 tweets of, first, Rahul Gandhi and then Narendra Modi. We will capture only the time, id and text of the tweet and convert that into a dataframe for further preprocessing and analysis.

In [98]:
def tweets(username):
    count = 5000
    try:     
        tweets = api.user_timeline(screen_name=username, 
                           count=count,
                           include_rts = False,
                           # Necessary to keep full_text 
                           # otherwise only the first 140 words are extracted
                           tweet_mode = 'extended'
                           )
        tweets_list = [[tweet.created_at, tweet.id, tweet.full_text] for tweet in tweets]
        tweets_df = pd.DataFrame(tweets_list, columns= ['tweet_time', 'tweet_id', 'tweet'])

    except BaseException as e:
          print('failed on_status,',str(e))
          time.sleep(3)
    return tweets_df

Thenwe shall lemmatize allwords so that te different grammatical formsof same words can be consolidated into individualwords.

In [112]:
wordnet_lemmatizer = WordNetLemmatizer()

def lemma(sen):
    sen_token = nltk.word_tokenize(sen)
    lemma_word = []
    for w in sen_token:
        word1 = wordnet_lemmatizer.lemmatize(w, pos = "n")
        word2 = wordnet_lemmatizer.lemmatize(word1, pos = "v")
        word3 = wordnet_lemmatizer.lemmatize(word2, pos = ("a"))
        lemma_word.append(word3)
    return ' '.join(lemma_word)
In [113]:

In [114]:
stop_words_1 = set(stopwords.words('english'))
stop_words_2 = set(STOPWORDS)
stop_words_2.update(["amp","will","shri","S","ji","today","year","India","people","Day","ha", 'wa','thank','RT', 'The', 'This', 'A',
                    'I','Ji','In',"At",'It','He','His','On','ji'])
stop_words = stop_words_1.union(stop_words_2)
